Not so much an issue as a question about using a trampoline class, and perhaps something worth adding to the documentation.

I'm finding cases in my library where I want to bind both a base class with virtual methods and some derived classes of the base class, to allow the python classes to themselves inherit from either the base or derived classes.  As a concrete example, consider:

```C++
class A {
public:
    virtual void methodA1();
    virtual void methodA2();
    virtual void methodA3();
    virtual void methodA4();
};
class B : public A {
public:
    virtual void methodA1() override;
    void methodA2() override;
    virtual void methodB1();
};
class C : public B {
public:
    virtual void methodC1();
};

// Trampoline classes
class PyA : public A {
public:
    void methodA1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA1); }
    void methodA2() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA2); }
    void methodA3() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA3); }
    void methodA4() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA4); }
};
class PyB : public B {
    void methodA1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, methodA1); }
    // B's overridden methodA2() not virtual
    void methodA3() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, methodA3); }
    void methodA4() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, methodA4); }
    void methodB1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, methodB1); }
};
class PyC : public C {
    void methodA1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, C, methodA1); }
    void methodA3() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, C, methodA3); }
    void methodA4() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, C, methodA4); }
    void methodB1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, C, methodB1); }
    void methodC1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, C, methodC1); }
};
```

The thing that bothers me here is the duplication of virtual methods in PyB and PyC; this is also a bit error prone as it isn't enough to just look for virtual methods in B and C, I also need to remember to look at their ancestors for any virtual methods (methods 2 and 3, above).

So my question is this: am I missing something here that pybind11 is handling that I'm not aware of?  Is there (or could there be) a nicer way to do this that doesn't require repeating all the virtual methods in each trampoline class for each derived class?

To the latter question, the first though that occurred to me was that this could be accomplished via multiple inheritance (PyB inherits from both PyA and B), but that introduces diamond inheritance which would need `virtual` inheritance from A in both PyA (fine) and B (not so fine as it requires a C++ API change); I'm also not entirely sure that the method resolution order would be entirely correct.

Another potential solution is to template PyA, along the lines of:
```C++
template <class Base, typename = typename std::enable_if<std::is_base_of<A, Base>::value>::type>
class PyA : public Base {
public:
    virtual void methodA1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA1); }
    virtual void methodA2() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA2); }
    virtual void methodA3() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA3); }
    virtual void methodA4() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, A, methodA4); }
};
template <class Base, typename = typename std::enable_if<std::is_base_of<B, Base>::value>::type>
class PyB : public PyA<Base> {
public:
    virtual void methodA1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, methodA1); }
    virtual void methodB1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, B, methodB1); }
};
template <class Base, typename = typename std::enable_if<std::is_base_of<C, Base>::value>::type>
class PyC : public PyB<Base> {
public:
    virtual void methodC1() override { PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(void, C, methodC1); }
};
```
and then using `PyA<A>` for A's trampoline class and `PyB<B>` for B's trampoline class, and `PyC<C>` for C's.  I *think* this would get everything right (as long as all the trampoline methods are themselves virtual), while being both cleaner and far less likely to accidentally miss a base class virtual method.

Does this seem right to you, and if so, is it worth my writing it up as a documentation patch?

